{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_4041_1253_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_4041_1253_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*1253
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The juvenile court asserted dependency jurisdiction over an incorrigible teenager, 17\u8211\'3fyear\u8211\'3fold Precious D., under 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_a83b000018c76" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Welfare and Institutions Code section 300, subdivision (b)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, and removed her from the custody of her mother, Patricia D. (Mother).
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_B00112023628745_ID0ESDAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_B00112023628745_ID0ESDAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_B00112023628745_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
1
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_7047_529_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_7047_529_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
**529
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In this case of first impression, we address the issue of whether the provision of 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_a83b000018c76" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 300(b)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 providing for jurisdiction based on the parent\rquote s \u8220\'3finability ... to adequately supervise or protect the child\u8221\'3f requires that the parent be unfit or neglectful in causing serious physical harm to the child or a 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_4041_1254_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_4041_1254_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*1254
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 risk of such harm. We hold that, in light of the dependency statutory scheme and federal due process principles, parental unfitness or neglectful conduct must be shown in order to assert dependency court jurisdiction under that part of 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_a83b000018c76" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 300(b)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 providing for jurisdiction based on the parent\rquote s \u8220\'3finability ... to adequately supervise or protect the child.\u8221\'3f Because there was insufficient evidence of both unfitness and neglectful conduct in this case, we reverse the jurisdiction and disposition orders.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_Ib050aaea11ac11e498db8b09b4f04}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_Ib050aaea11ac11e498db8b09b4f04}
\par 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_Ib050aaea11ac11e498db8b09b4f04}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_Ib050aaea11ac11e498db8b09b4f04}
\par 
{\b0 \qc \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb600 
BACKGROUND
\par 
}
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Precious D., born in August 1992, lived with Mother and Precious\rquote s two half sisters, ages 14 and 8. Mother\rquote s male companion, Onajite E. (Stepfather), was the father of Precious\rquote s half sisters and visited their home often, but did not live there. Precious\rquote s father, Steven B., lived in Arizona, last visited with Precious in 2002, and did not appear in these proceedings. When Precious was 16 years old, she started associating with the \u8220\'3fwrong crowd,\u8221\'3f talked to \u8220\'3folder guys\u8221\'3f on the phone, met up with people she met on the phone, misbehaved, missed classes, and started running away from home. Mother suspected that Precious was engaging in prostitution, but Precious denied it.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In March 2009, the Los Angeles County Department of Children and Family Services (DCFS) received a referral from the Los Angeles Police Department that Precious was a runaway and that she was picked up by the police in Long Beach. Precious asserted that her Stepfather beat her; she refused to return home to Mother. A police detective told DCFS that there was no evidence of abuse, and DCFS concluded that the allegations of physical abuse were unfounded.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Although Precious consistently maintained that Stepfather physically abused her by hitting her with an extension cord, Precious was unable to provide specific dates, times, instances, or motives for such physical punishment. Mother denied ever physically abusing Precious and told DCFS that she was willing and able to protect Precious from any abuse and wanted Precious to return home, but Mother needed support to help her address Precious\rquote s mental health needs. Stepfather was hurt and shocked by Precious\rquote s allegations of abuse; he denied ever hitting Precious or her half sisters. He told DCFS that they had been trying everything to help Precious, and when she ran away, they would look day and night to find her. Precious\rquote s half sisters also denied any abuse in the home. Precious \u8220\'3fremains adamant that she is not afraid of [Mother],\u8221\'3f but it was unclear to DCFS why Precious ran away from home and did not want to return to Mother.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_4041_1255_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_4041_1255_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*1255
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 On March 12, 2009, Mother signed a Voluntary Family Reunification Contract and Precious was placed in a foster home. The next day, Precious ran away from the foster home. Precious\rquote s foster mother reported that Precious was sneaking boys into the home and that she had taken Precious to the emergency room because she had contracted a 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?entityType=disease&entityId=Ic8edbc8c475411db9765f9243f53508a&originationContext=document&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Default)&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
sexually transmitted 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_7047_530_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_7047_530_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
**530
}
}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 disease
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, chlamydia. According to Precious, she received medication for a 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?entityType=disease&entityId=Ic63aaaed475411db9765f9243f53508a&originationContext=document&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Default)&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
bladder infection
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In April 2009, Precious was placed in a second foster home, where she was disrespectful, left without permission, refused to follow the house rules, skipped classes, and sent threatening and inappropriate messages to her family. Mother and Precious spoke by telephone daily, but Precious refused to see Mother or her half sisters. In April 2009, Precious told a DCFS social worker that she had a boyfriend who was 20 years old. Precious also persisted in her claim that she had been the victim of a gang rape, even though Mother had taken her to the hospital and a rape examination revealed no trauma.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
After a month in the second foster, Precious\rquote s foster mother reported that Precious was engaging in behaviors such as missing classes in school, running away, stealing, and leaving home to \u8220\'3fhang out with boys.\u8221\'3f The foster mother told DCFS that Precious \u8220\'3fcraves attention and dresses very provocative[ly].\u8221\'3f Although the foster mother had requested that Precious be placed in another home, the foster mother agreed to continue with Precious\rquote s placement to allow her to receive mental health services.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In June 2009, the foster family agency reported that Precious was enrolled in mental health counseling but was not on any medication and had not begun family therapy. Mother continued to telephone Precious daily, but because of transportation problems had not visited with her; the foster family agency then agreed to transport Mother for visits with Precious. Precious\rquote s foster mother reported that the mental health counseling did not seem to be making an impact on Precious\rquote s behavior, as Precious refused to do any chores, missed classes every day, and \u8220\'3fall [she] wants to do is run away and fight.\u8221\'3f Mother telephoned Precious often, but Precious refused to see Mother. During a July 6, 2009 meeting with a social worker, Precious was very emotional, refused to return home, and blamed Mother for her bad grades and behavior. Precious reiterated her claim that Stepfather beat her; Precious also said that Stepfather beat Mother and \u8220\'3fcontrols the house.\u8221\'3f Precious claimed that no one was on her side or believed her.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
During a July 14, 2009 psychiatric assessment, Precious stated that she wanted to hurt herself, so she was admitted to a psychiatric hospital on a 72\u8211\'3fhour hold. Precious was diagnosed with 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?entityType=disease&entityId=Ib7c7c836475411db9765f9243f53508a&originationContext=document&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Default)&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
major depression
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, but was 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_4041_1256_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_4041_1256_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*1256
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 released from the hospital on July 17, 2009, without medication being prescribed. On July 20, 2009, a team decision-making meeting was held to determine whether Precious needed a higher level of care or whether she could be returned home with intensive services. As a result of the meeting, a safety plan was created that included family therapy and placement of Precious in a group home where it would be ensured that she received appropriate mental health services.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
After Precious was placed in a group home on July 20, 2009, she called the social worker several times, threatening to run away if she was not placed with the maternal grandfather. DCFS did not allow Precious visitation with the maternal grandparents because the issue of their criminal backgrounds first needed to be resolved. In August 2009, Precious was suspended from school because of her disruptive behavior; she asserted that the school staff harassed her for no apparent reason. Precious remained placed in the group home at the time of the jurisdiction and disposition hearing in November 2009.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
According to the DCFS service log for July 20, 2009, DCFS decided to bring the 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_7047_531_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_7047_531_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
**531
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 family to the attention of the juvenile court because Precious refused to return home and Mother said that she could not care for Precious\rquote s special needs. DCFS later wrote in a report that \u8220\'3f[d]ue to the child\rquote s incorrigible behaviors, it was determined that a petition must be filed on behalf of the child for court ordered services.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
On July 31, 2009, DCFS filed a dependency petition as to Precious, but not as to her half sisters, who remained in Mother\rquote s custody. The petition contained allegations against Mother under 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_a83b000018c76" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 300(b)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (failure or inability to protect). Allegations against Stepfather under 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_8b3b0000958a4" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 300, subdivisions (a)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (serious physical harm) and (b) were later dismissed.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In the September 2009 jurisdiction/disposition report, DCFS reported that Precious was cooperative during group therapy sessions, was participating in individual therapy, anger management, and drug and alcohol counseling. She also was prescribed psychotropic medications of 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?entityType=bdrug&entityId=I37eaf688475111db9765f9243f53508a&originationContext=document&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Default)&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Abilify
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 and Oxcarbadepine. With respect to visitation, the DCFS report stated, \u8220\'3fNo visitation orders have been made to date as to the family. DCFS recommends monitored visitation for the mother and child in a therapeutic setting. The mother and child have not had any face to face visits to date as the minor has refused to visit with the mother, however both mother and child report talking on the telephone almost daily.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_4041_1257_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_4041_1257_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*1257
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In preparation of its report, DCFS interviewed Mother, who told DCFS that Precious had run away from home numerous times; each time, Mother had filed a police report, except for the second time when Mother thought that Precious would come right back. On one occasion, Mother searched Precious\rquote s room and found out where she was staying; Mother, Stepfather, and the maternal grandfather went looking for Precious, asking people about her and showing them her picture. On two occasions, Mother sent Precious to live with her maternal aunts, but that did not work out because Precious ran away from the aunts\rquote  homes. Mother said that she had \u8220\'3ftried everything with Precious.\u8221\'3f According to Mother, Precious admitted to making up a story about being raped and held hostage. After Precious was placed in foster care, she called Mother several times to ask if she could come home and to apologize for lying. Mother told DCFS that \u8220\'3f \u8216\'3fI just want Precious to get some help before she comes home. I have always wanted her and I still want her to come home, but she needs help.\u8217\'3f \u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In its report, DCFS alleged that there were four problems requiring intervention: (1) an ongoing conflict between Precious and Mother such that Mother \u8220\'3fis unable to care for the minor due to the minor\rquote s extreme behavioral problems\u8221\'3f; (2) the unwillingness of Precious to return home; (3) the physical abuse of Precious by \u8220\'3fone or more adults in the home\u8221\'3f; and (4) the failure of the family to benefit from prior voluntary family maintenance services. Notwithstanding the foregoing alleged problems, DCFS\rquote s report admitted that, other than assertions by Precious, there was no other evidence of physical abuse; that juvenile court jurisdiction was sought because of Precious\rquote s incorrigible behavior and her need for court-ordered services; that Mother felt that she was in need of services to help her control Precious\rquote s behavior; that Mother was concerned about her financial ability to provide care for Precious while she was in placement; that the reason why the family therapy called for by the safety plan was never initiated was because Precious refused to see Mother; that Mother expressed a willingness to participate in services to assist reunification; that Precious was not afraid of Mother; that Precious felt safe in Mother\rquote s 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_7047_532_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_7047_532_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
**532
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 care; and that \u8220\'3f[t]here remains open communication between the mother and the child, despite the current circumstances.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
At the jurisdiction and disposition hearing on November 24, 2009, the juvenile court admitted into evidence DCFS\rquote s detention and jurisdiction/disposition reports and heard argument of counsel. Mother requested that the court dismiss the petition on the ground that Precious\rquote s incorrigible behavior was an insufficient reason to assert dependency court jurisdiction. The court denied Mother\rquote s request and sustained a count under 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_a83b000018c76" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 300(b)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 that was 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_4041_1258_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_4041_1258_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*1258
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 amended to state that Precious \u8220\'3fis unwilling to return to the mother\rquote s home and has repeatedly gone AWOL. Additionally, [Mother has] been unable to provide ongoing supervision of this child. Said inability of the child\rquote s mother endangers the child\rquote s physical and emotional health and safety and places the child at risk of harm.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The juvenile court explained its denial of Mother\rquote s request to dismiss the petition and its assertion of jurisdiction under 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_a83b000018c76" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 300(b)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 as follows: \u8220\'3fI think the documents presented by the department are clear that there is a substantial risk that this child is going to suffer physical harm based upon what has been her behavior of running away, being AWOL, being incorrigible, and her mother has the inability to supervise or protect her daughter because the parent, the mother, and the daughter are not communicating. [\u182\'3f] And the court feels that the department has met [its] burden of showing that this is a child at risk of being abused or neglected, some of which is through her mother\rquote s inability to control her and some of which is Precious\rquote s behavior of not wanting to comply. [\u182\'3f] But the result is still the same in that Precious is somebody that comes within the jurisdiction of this court. And so the court is going to sustain [count b\u8211\'3f2 of the petition] as amended.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
As to disposition, the juvenile court removed Precious from Mother\rquote s custody. With respect to family reunification services, Mother\rquote s attorney requested that the court order only family therapy when appropriate, and not parenting or individual counseling for Mother. DCFS agreed that a parenting class would not benefit Mother. The court then agreed to follow Mother\rquote s request, \u8220\'3fsince we\rquote re all very clear that the issue\rquote s Precious, not [Mother].\u8221\'3f The court then ordered therapy for Mother and Precious when Precious\rquote s therapist deemed it appropriate. For Precious, the court ordered individual counseling, a tutoring referral, and an ILP (independent living skills program) referral. The court ordered that Mother\rquote s visits were unmonitored, and the visits were not to include Stepfather. The court also ordered Precious, who attended the hearing, to visit with Mother. The court told Precious, \u8220\'3fI need you to be clear that I expect you to work with this court in fixing what is wrong. I don\rquote t believe it is all your mother\rquote s fault. I believe you are responsible for some of the damage that\rquote s been done.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Mother appeals from the jurisdiction and disposition orders, raising challenges to the sufficiency of the evidence.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
