{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u8220\'3f \u8216\'3fWhen the sufficiency of the evidence to support a finding or order is challenged on appeal, the reviewing court must determine if there is any substantial evidence, that is, evidence which is reasonable, credible, and of 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_4041_1259_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_4041_1259_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*1259
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 solid value to support the conclusion of the trier of fact. [Citation.] In making this determination, all conflicts [in the evidence and in reasonable inferences from the evidence] are to be resolved in favor of the prevailing party, and 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_7047_533_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_7047_533_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
**533
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 issues of fact and credibility are questions for the trier of fact. [Citation.]\u8217\'3f \u8221\'3f (
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2006976012&pubNum=7047&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In re Savannah M.
}
}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (2005) 131 Cal.App.4th 1387, 1393, 32 Cal.Rptr.3d 526.)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 While substantial evidence may consist of inferences, such inferences must rest on the evidence; inferences that are the result of speculation or conjecture cannot support a finding. 
}
