}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 \u8220\'3fA jurisdictional finding under 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_a83b000018c76" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 300, subdivision (b)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 requires: \u8216\'3f \u8220\'3f(1) neglectful conduct by the parent in one of the specified forms; (2) causation; and (3) \u8216\'3fserious physical harm or illness\rquote  to the child, or a \u8216\'3fsubstantial risk\u8217\'3f of such harm or illness.\u8221\'3f [Citation.]\rquote  [Citations.]\u8221\'3f (
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2019393050&pubNum=7047&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In re James R.
}
}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (2009) 176 Cal.App.4th 129, 135, 97 Cal.Rptr.3d 310.)
}}}
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_anchor_F22023628745_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[2]
}}}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_B22023628745_1}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_B22023628745_1}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The juvenile court in this case made only one finding that can be construed as critical of Mother\rquote s parenting skills or conduct, and that is the finding that Mother and Precious were not communicating. But this finding is not supported by substantial evidence because the record shows that Mother and Precious were in daily telephone contact. DCFS\rquote s jurisdiction/disposition report also noted as a 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
family strength
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 that there was \u8220\'3fopen communication between the mother and the child, despite the current circumstances.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Nor is there substantial evidence in the record to fault Mother for the failure to initiate family therapy and the failure of the voluntary family reunification plan. It was undisputed that Mother was willing to participate in therapy, but it was Precious who was refusing to see Mother. DCFS did not initiate family therapy because of Precious\rquote s conduct, not Mother\rquote s. DCFS admitted that it sought dependency court jurisdiction because of Precious\rquote s incorrigible behavior and her need for court-ordered services, not because of any neglectful conduct by Mother. It is also apparent that there was no neglectful conduct by Mother because Mother was not ordered to participate in any services except family counseling with Precious, when Precious\rquote s therapist deemed it appropriate. Mother was always ready and willing to participate in family counseling. We thus conclude that there is insufficient evidence of unfitness or neglectful conduct by Mother.
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
