DCFS contends that jurisdiction is proper under 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_a83b000018c76" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 300(b)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 if there is an 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
inability
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 on Mother\rquote s part to supervise or protect Precious, notwithstanding the lack of any neglectful conduct by Mother. DCFS argues that the 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_4041_1260_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_4041_1260_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*1260
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 inclusion of the words \u8220\'3fwillful or negligent failure\u8221\'3f in other clauses of 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_a83b000018c76" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 300(b)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, but not in the clause at issue here (see fn. 1, 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
ante
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 ), indicates a legislative intent that neither parental unfitness nor neglectful conduct is required to assert jurisdiction.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_anchor_F32023628745_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[3]
}}}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_B32023628745_1}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_B32023628745_1}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 As DCFS points out in its brief, this is a case of first impression as to whether parental unfitness or neglectful conduct is required for the assertion of jurisdiction based on a parent\rquote s \u8220\'3finability ... to adequately supervise or protect the child.\u8221\'3f As we explain below, we reject DCFS\rquote s interpretation of 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_a83b000018c76" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 300(b)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 because it would not comport with due process principles and the dependency process viewed as a whole.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_anchor_F42023628745_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[4]
}}}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_B42023628745_1}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_B42023628745_1}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 \u8220\'3fGiven the complexity of the statutory scheme governing dependency, a single provision \u8216\'3fcannot properly be understood 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_7047_534_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_7047_534_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
**534
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 except in the context of the entire dependency process of which it is a part.\u8217\'3f [Citation.]\u8221\'3f (
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2018493758&pubNum=4645&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In re Nolan W.
}
}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (2009) 45 Cal.4th 1217, 1235, 91 Cal.Rptr.3d 140, 203 P.3d 454.)
}}}
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The nature of the dependency statutory scheme from the parent\rquote s perspective was explained as follows in 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1997160089&pubNum=3484&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In re Meranda P.
}
}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (1997) 56 Cal.App.4th 1143, 65 Cal.Rptr.2d 913:
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 \u8220\'3fThe dependency scheme is a \u8216\'3fremarkable system of checks and balances\rquote  [citation] designed to \u8216\'3fpreserve the parent-child relationship and to reduce the risk of erroneous fact-finding in ... many different ways....\rquote  [Citation.] Until permanency planning, the parent\rquote s interest in having a child returned to the parent is the paramount concern of the law. [Citations.] The parent is thus entitled to 12 months, and possibly 6 more months, of reunification services aimed at assisting the parent in overcoming the problems that led to the child\rquote s removal. [Citations.] There is also in force at the dispositional hearing and at all subsequent prepermanency planning hearings a statutory presumption that the child will be returned to parental custody. [Citations.] [\u182\'3f] In addition, there are \u8216\'3fprecise and demanding substantive and procedural requirements\rquote  which the petitioning agency must fulfill before it can propose termination. At the dispositional hearing, the agency must show by the enhanced standard of clear and convincing evidence that removal of the child is necessary. [Citation.] ... Before reunification can be terminated, the agency must establish by a preponderance of evidence that it would be detrimental to return the child to the parent. [Citations.]\u8221\'3f 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1997160089&pubNum=3484&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
(
}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Meranda P.,
}
}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 at p. 1154, 65 Cal.Rptr.2d 913.)
}}}
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
