{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_B102023628745_1}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_B102023628745_1}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Due process guarantees apply to dependency proceedings. (
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2020747477&pubNum=7047&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In re A.S.
}
}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (2009) 180 Cal.App.4th 351, 359, 102 Cal.Rptr.3d 642.)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 \u8220\'3fIn deciding requirements of due process, the court evaluates three elements: the private 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_4041_1261_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_4041_1261_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*1261
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 interests at stake, the government\rquote s interest, and the risk the procedures used will lead to an erroneous decision. [Citations.] [\u182\'3f] The private interest at stake in a dependency proceeding is enormous. A parent\rquote s interest in the companionship, care, custody and management of his or her children is a fundamental civil right. [Citation.] Children, too, have a compelling independent interest in belonging to their natural family. [Citation.] In addition, each child has a compelling interest to live free from abuse and neglect in a stable, permanent placement with an emotionally committed caregiver. [Citation.] The governmental interest in a child\rquote s welfare is significant. \u8216\'3f[T]he welfare of a child is a compelling state interest that a state has not only a right, but a duty, to protect.\u8217\'3f [Citations.]\u8221\'3f (
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2007196889&pubNum=7047&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In re Dakota H.
}
}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (2005) 132 Cal.App.4th 212, 222\u8211\'3f223, 33 Cal.Rptr.3d 337.)
}}}
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_anchor_F112023628745_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[11]
}}}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_B112023628745_1}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_B112023628745_1}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 \u8220\'3fThe California dependency system comports with federal due process requirements because \u8216\'3f[t]he number and quality of the judicial findings that are necessary preconditions to termination convey very powerfully to the fact finder the subjective certainty about parental unfitness and detriment required before the court may even consider ending the relationship between natural parent and child.\u8217\'3f [Citation.]\u8221\'3f (
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2020747477&pubNum=7047&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In re A.S., supra,
}
}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 180 Cal.App.4th at p. 359, 102 Cal.Rptr.3d 642.)
}}}
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Under DCFS\rquote s construction of 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=SP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)#co_pp_a83b000018c76" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
section 300(b)
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, dependency jurisdiction may be asserted over an incorrigible child whose parent is neither unfit nor neglectful. If so, such a jurisdictional finding would then be the basis for the child\rquote s removal and for an order requiring reunification services that are either unnecessary or doomed to failure due to incorrigible conduct on the child\rquote s part, and then for the ultimate termination of parental rights. Thus, parental rights would be terminated and the 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_7047_535_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_7047_535_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
**535
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 family unit destroyed without any finding of unfitness or neglectful conduct. Such a result would not comport with federal due process principles.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
For all of the foregoing reasons, we conclude that substantial evidence does not support the assertion of dependency court jurisdiction over Precious. \u8220\'3fIn light of our determination that the jurisdictional order must be reversed, the dispositional order placing the children outside mother\rquote s home and all subsequent orders as to mother must be reversed as well.\u8221\'3f (
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2019363614&pubNum=7047&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In re R.M.
}
}
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (2009) 175 Cal.App.4th at 986, 991, 96 Cal.Rptr.3d 655.)
}}}
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Our juvenile court system is not without recourse and resources to deal with an incorrigible minor, notwithstanding the lack of dependency jurisdiction in the circumstances of this case. (See, e.g., \u167\'3f 601 et seq. [providing procedure to adjudge a habitually disobedient or truant minor a ward of the court]; \u167\'3f 241.1 [providing procedure for minor who \u8220\'3fappears to come within the description of both 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS300&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=LQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf28 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Section 300
}}}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 and 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://wwwtest.int.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000228&cite=CAWIS601&originatingDoc=I465a5b3aeb7211dfaa23bccc834e9520&refType=LQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.History*oc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
